    "faq": {
      "type": "lsc-faq",
      "blocks": {
        "faq_1": {
          "type": "faq",
          "settings": {
            "question": "What causes red veins and thread veins?",
            "answer": "<p>Thread veins (also known as spider veins or telangiectasia) form when small blood vessels close to the skin surface dilate permanently. Common causes include sun damage, rosacea, hormonal changes, genetics, ageing, and prolonged standing. They are harmless but can cause cosmetic concern.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_2": {
          "type": "faq",
          "settings": {
            "question": "How does the treatment work?",
            "answer": "<p>We use targeted light or laser energy that is selectively absorbed by haemoglobin in the blood vessels. The heat generated causes the vessel walls to collapse and seal. The treated vessels are then gradually reabsorbed by the body over the following weeks.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_3": {
          "type": "faq",
          "settings": {
            "question": "How many sessions will I need?",
            "answer": "<p>Most superficial facial thread veins respond within 1–3 sessions. Leg veins or more widespread redness may require more sessions. Your consultation includes an honest assessment of the number of sessions likely needed.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_4": {
          "type": "faq",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Is the treatment painful?",
            "answer": "<p>The treatment is generally well tolerated. You may feel a brief warming or snapping sensation as each vessel is targeted. Facial treatments are typically very comfortable; leg vein treatment may be slightly more intense.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_5": {
          "type": "faq",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Will the veins come back?",
            "answer": "<p>Treated veins are permanently sealed. However, new thread veins can develop over time, particularly with continued sun exposure, hormonal changes, or genetics. Most clients return annually for maintenance.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_6": {
          "type": "faq",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Can I have treatment if I have rosacea?",
            "answer": "<p>Yes — treating the visible vessels associated with rosacea can significantly reduce redness and flushing. The underlying condition is not cured, but the visible signs are dramatically reduced. A patch test is always performed first.</p>"
          }
        }
      },
